    "summary": "I\u2019m an experimental physicist with an interest in condensed matter and correlated quantum systems. \nCurrently in my PhD in the Otte Lab, I\u2019m working on detecting and controlling the properties of magnetic atoms on a surface. We combine Electron Spin Resonance (ESR) and Scanning Tunneling Microscopy (STM) to achieve incredible energy resolution on short time scales, localized for a single atom. This allows us to measure the coherent evolution of spin excitations [1]. In the coming years, I hope to expand the quantum systems we can investigate with this method and learn something new about excitations in correlated matter.\n\nI did my Masters at Leiden University. In a first master research project in the Allan Lab, I looked at cuprates (high-temperature superconductors) in the overdoped regime using Scanning Tunneling Spectroscopy (STS). The phenomenological patterns I tried to find could lead to a better understanding on how superconductivity disappears again if you dope higher than the optimal.\n\nDuring my second master research project in the Oosterkamp group, I worked on assembling a novel Magnetic Resonance Force Microscope (MRFM) that operates at milliKelvin temperatures by employing a SQUID (superconducting quantum interference device).\n\nAside from my experience in physics, I have acquired graphical design skills after working on yearbooks for SSR-Leiden and De Leidsche Flesch.\n\nIn my free time, I like to cook (and eat it too!). I enjoy some gaming and reading. I also do rock climbing to stay fit and get the stress out of my system. \n\n[1] Veldman, L. M., Farinacci, L., Rejali, R., Broekhoven, R., Gobeil, J., Coffey, D., \u2026 Otte, A. F. (2021). Free coherent evolution of a coupled atomic spin system initialized by electron scattering. Science, 372(6545), 964\u2013968. https://doi.org/10.1126/science.abg8223",
